To detect if a webpage is being automated by Selenium using ChromeDriver, you can check for specific properties that are typically present when Selenium is in use. Below is an example code snippet demonstrating how to do this using JavaScript:

```javascript
const { Builder, By } = require('selenium-webdriver');

(async function detectSelenium() {
    // Create a new instance of the ChromeDriver
    let driver = await new Builder().forBrowser('chrome').build();

    try {
        // Navigate to the desired URL
        await driver.get('https://www.example.com');

        // Check for common indicators of Selenium usage
        const userAgent = await driver.executeScript("return navigator.userAgent;");

        if (userAgent.includes("HeadlessChrome")) {
            console.log("Detected: Headless Chrome (likely running with Selenium)");
        }

        const webdriverProperty = await driver.executeScript("return window.navigator.webdriver;");

        if (webdriverProperty) {
            console.log("Detected: Webdriver property set (indicates automation by Selenium)");
        }

    } catch (error) {
       console.error(`Error occurred: ${error}`);
    } finally {
       // Quit the browser session after detection checks are complete
       await driver.quit();
   }
})();
```

In this code:
- We import necessary modules from `selenium-webdriver`.
- We create an asynchronous function `detectSelenium` to encapsulate our logic.
- A new instance of ChromeDriver is created and navigated to a specified URL.
- The script checks for two common indicators:
  - The presence of "HeadlessChrome" in the user agent string.
  - The value of `window.navigator.webdriver`, which indicates that WebDriver has been used.
- Finally, we ensure that we quit the browser session regardless of whether an error occurs or not.

