To use the Process Environment Block (PEB) for anti-debugging, you can check specific flags and attributes within the PEB to determine if your application is being debugged. The PEB contains information about the process environment, including whether a debugger is attached.

Here’s an example of how you might implement this in C#:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Diagnostics;
using System.Runtime.InteropServices;

class Program
{
    [DllImport("kernel32.dll")]
    static extern IntPtr GetCurrentProcess();

    [DllImport("kernel32.dll")]
    static extern bool IsDebuggerPresent();

    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        if (IsDebuggerPresent())
        {
            Console.WriteLine("Debugging detected! Exiting...");
            return; // Exit or take other actions to prevent debugging.
        }

        // Your main program logic here
        Console.WriteLine("Running without debugger.");

        // Additional code...

        var env = new Environment();
        env.Message = "This message will not be shown if debugging is detected.";

       // Further processing...

       Console.WriteLine(env.Message);
   }
}

public class Environment
{
   public string Message { get; set; }
}
```

In this code snippet, we utilize `IsDebuggerPresent()` from the Windows API to check if a debugger is currently attached. If it detects that a debugger is present, it outputs a warning message and exits early. This method effectively prevents further execution of your program while under debug conditions.

By leveraging these techniques with the PEB and related APIs, you can create more robust applications that resist reverse engineering efforts by detecting when they are being analyzed in a debugging environment.

